        overview: "Atomic structure is the foundational framework of all chemistry. Every chemical property вҖ” reactivity, bonding, periodicity, spectroscopy вҖ” is ultimately rooted in how protons, neutrons, and electrons are arranged within atoms. Understanding atomic structure means understanding why elements behave as they do: why sodium is reactive, why carbon forms four bonds, why noble gases are inert, and why the periodic table is arranged as it is.",
        whyItMatters: "Modern technology depends entirely on precise knowledge of atomic structure. Semiconductors, MRI scanners, nuclear power, mass spectrometry in drug testing, radioisotopes in cancer treatment вҖ” all rely on manipulating atomic properties. The electronic configuration of an atom determines which bonds it forms, which reactions it undergoes, and what its compounds look like. Without atomic structure, there is no chemistry.",
        bigPicture: "Atoms are not indivisible вҖ” they contain a dense, positive nucleus (protons and neutrons) surrounded by a much larger region occupied by electrons. Electrons do not orbit randomly; they occupy specific energy levels (shells), each divided into subshells (s, p, d, f), each containing orbitals with defined shapes. The number and arrangement of electrons determine an element's chemical identity. Removing electrons (ionisation) requires energy that can be measured precisely вҖ” and successive ionisation energies provide direct experimental evidence for the shell model.",
