    topicIntroduction: {
        overview: "Organic chemistry is the study of carbon-containing compounds and their transformations. While hydrocarbons establish the carbon skeleton, it is the functional groups вҖ” specific arrangements of atoms attached to that skeleton вҖ” that define how organic molecules react. Mastering organic chemistry means understanding how each functional group reacts, why it reacts that way mechanistically, and how reactions can be chained together into synthetic routes to build target molecules.",
        whyItMatters: "Every pharmaceutical drug, polymer, dye, flavour, and fragrance is an organic compound whose properties are determined by its functional groups. Ethanol (an alcohol) powers biofuels and is the active ingredient in alcoholic drinks and antiseptics. Halogenoalkanes are used as refrigerants, anaesthetics, and synthetic intermediates. Carbonyl compounds appear in virtually every biochemical pathway вҖ” glucose, fats, and amino acids all contain carbonyl groups. Understanding functional group chemistry is the gateway to biochemistry, pharmacology, materials science, and synthetic chemistry.",
        bigPicture: "Organic chemistry is unified by mechanism вҖ” the step-by-step movement of electrons from nucleophiles (electron donors) to electrophiles (electron acceptors). Each functional group presents a distinct electronic environment: the CвҖ“OH bond in alcohols, the CвҖ“X bond in halogenoalkanes, the C=O bond in carbonyl compounds. Knowing the electron-rich and electron-poor sites in each group allows the reactivity to be predicted and the mechanism drawn from first principles.",
        priorKnowledge: [
            "Hydrocarbon classification: alkanes, alkenes, arenes and their reactivity patterns",
            "Nucleophiles and electrophiles: electron-rich species donate to electron-poor sites",
            "Curly arrow notation: double-headed for ionic (two-electron) steps",
            "Electronegativity and bond polarity: CвҖ“X, C=O bonds are polarised",
            "Oxidation states of carbon: from alkane (reduced) to carboxylic acid (oxidised)",
            "Free-radical substitution and electrophilic addition from hydrocarbon chemistry"
        ],
        topicRoadmap: [
            "Functional groups: classification and interconversion overview",
            "Alcohols: primary, secondary, tertiary classification; oxidation, substitution, elimination, esterification",
            "Phenols: acidic character, reaction with sodium, bromine water, and acylation",
            "Halogenoalkanes: bond polarity, nucleophilic substitution (SN1 and SN2), elimination",
            "Rate of hydrolysis: effect of CвҖ“X bond strength (F > Cl > Br > I bond strength; I fastest hydrolysis)",
            "Carbonyl compounds: aldehydes vs ketones; nucleophilic addition; distinguishing tests",
            "Carboxylic acids: acidity, reactions with bases, alcohols (esterification), and reducing agents",
            "Esters: formation, hydrolysis (acid and base), uses",
            "Acyl chlorides and acid anhydrides: nucleophilic acyl substitution",
            "Amines: basicity, reaction with acids, acylation",
            "Amino acids and proteins: peptide bond formation and hydrolysis",
            "Organic synthesis: functional group interconversions and multi-step route planning"
        ]
    },

    concepts: [
        "Functional groups are the reactive sites of organic molecules; the carbon skeleton is largely inert",
        "Primary, secondary, and tertiary alcohols are oxidised to different products by acidified dichromate",
        "Halogenoalkanes are electrophilic at carbon due to the CвҖ“X bond dipole; they react with nucleophiles",
        "SN1 and SN2 mechanisms differ in molecularity, stereochemistry, and substrate preference",
        "The C=O group is the reactive site in aldehydes, ketones, carboxylic acids, esters, and amides",
        "Aldehydes are oxidised to carboxylic acids; ketones resist oxidation вҖ” this difference enables their distinction",
        "Carboxylic acids are weak acids; their derivatives (esters, acyl chlorides, amides) undergo nucleophilic acyl substitution",
        "Organic synthesis requires planning a retrosynthetic route: identifying transformations that connect starting material to target molecule"
    ],

    theory: "The reactivity of organic compounds is governed by two factors: the electronic structure of the functional group (which atoms are electron-rich or electron-poor) and the mechanism by which electrons are transferred (substitution, addition, elimination, oxidation/reduction). Curly arrows represent the movement of electron pairs from nucleophile to electrophile. Each functional group has a characteristic mechanism: nucleophilic substitution for halogenoalkanes, nucleophilic addition for carbonyl compounds, and nucleophilic acyl substitution for carboxylic acid derivatives.",

    keyDefinitions: {
        "Functional Group":            "A specific atom or group of atoms within a molecule responsible for its characteristic chemical reactions",
        "Primary Alcohol":             "Alcohol in which the C bearing вҖ“OH is bonded to one other carbon (RвҖ“CHвӮӮOH)",
        "Secondary Alcohol":           "Alcohol in which the C bearing вҖ“OH is bonded to two other carbons (RвӮӮCHOH)",
        "Tertiary Alcohol":            "Alcohol in which the C bearing вҖ“OH is bonded to three other carbons (RвӮғCOH)",
        "Oxidation (organic)":         "Loss of hydrogen or gain of oxygen; shown by the reagent [O] (acidified potassium dichromate, KMnOвӮ„)",
        "Nucleophilic Substitution":   "A nucleophile displaces a leaving group from a carbon atom, forming a new bond",
        "Leaving Group":               "An atom or group that departs with the bonding electron pair during substitution; good leaving groups are stable anions (IвҒ», BrвҒ», ClвҒ»)",
        "SN1 Mechanism":               "Unimolecular nucleophilic substitution: two steps вҖ” ionisation to carbocation, then nucleophile attack; rate depends only on substrate concentration",
        "SN2 Mechanism":               "Bimolecular nucleophilic substitution: one concerted step вҖ” nucleophile attacks as leaving group departs; rate depends on both substrate and nucleophile concentration; inversion of configuration",
        "Elimination":                 "Removal of atoms from adjacent carbons to form a C=C double bond; competes with substitution in halogenoalkane reactions",
        "Carbonyl Group":              "C=O вҖ” the reactive centre in aldehydes (RCHO), ketones (RCOR'), carboxylic acids (RCOOH), esters (RCOOR'), and amides (RCONHвӮӮ)",
        "Nucleophilic Addition":       "A nucleophile attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon, breaking the C=O ПҖ bond and forming a tetrahedral intermediate",
        "Esterification":              "Condensation reaction between a carboxylic acid and an alcohol (or acyl chloride/anhydride and alcohol/phenol) to form an ester and water (or HCl/acid)",
        "Hydrolysis":                  "Breakdown of a compound by reaction with water; esters and amides hydrolyse to carboxylic acids (or salts) and alcohols (or amines)",
        "Acyl Chloride":               "Highly reactive carboxylic acid derivative (RCOCl); reacts vigorously with water, alcohols, and amines via nucleophilic acyl substitution",
        "Retrosynthesis":              "Planning a synthesis by working backwards from the target molecule to simpler starting materials, identifying the bond formed in each step",
        "Peptide Bond":                "Amide bond formed between the вҖ“COOH of one amino acid and the вҖ“NHвӮӮ of another, with loss of water"
    },

