        application: "Uranium: Z = 92. ВІВівҒөU: protons = 92, neutrons = 235 вҲ’ 92 = 143, electrons = 92. ВІВівҒёU: protons = 92, neutrons = 238 вҲ’ 92 = 146, electrons = 92. Both have Z = 92 вҶ’ both uranium вҶ’ isotopes confirmed (same proton number, different neutron number). Both have 92 electrons in identical configurations вҶ’ identical chemical behaviour. Separation is physical (by mass difference via centrifugal force), not chemical.",
        question: "Explain why gas centrifuges must be run in enormous cascades (thousands of stages) to produce weapons-grade uranium (>90% ВІВівҒөU) from natural uranium (0.7% ВІВівҒөU), given that the mass difference between ВІВівҒөUFвӮҶ and ВІВівҒёUFвӮҶ is only about 1.3%.",
        answer: "The mass difference between ВІВівҒөUFвӮҶ (m/z вүҲ 349) and ВІВівҒёUFвӮҶ (m/z вүҲ 352) is only ~0.86%, leading to only a very slight enrichment per centrifuge stage (separation factor Оұ вүҲ 1.004 per stage). To go from 0.7% to 90% ВІВівҒөU requires multiplying the ВІВівҒөU fraction by a factor of ~130 вҖ” this requires hundreds to thousands of cascaded centrifuge stages, with the slightly enriched output of each stage feeding into the next. This physical and engineering difficulty is the primary technical barrier to weapons proliferation.",
        extension: "The mass spectrometry used to verify enrichment levels in nuclear fuel is a direct application of the principles in this topic: UFвӮ…вҒә ions (formed by electron ionisation of UFвӮҶ) are separated at m/z = 333 (ВІВівҒөU) and m/z = 336 (ВІВівҒёU), and their peak heights give the isotope ratio precisely. International nuclear safeguards inspections use portable mass spectrometers to verify declared enrichment levels at nuclear facilities."
