        understand: "Explain why the Haber process uses a temperature of approximately 450В°C rather than 200В°C, even though the lower temperature would give a higher equilibrium yield of ammonia. Your answer must address both the kinetic argument (rate of reaction) and the thermodynamic argument (equilibrium position and Kc), and explain how the compromise temperature attempts to satisfy both requirements.",
        apply:      "The Contact process reaction 2SOвӮӮ(g) + OвӮӮ(g) вҮҢ 2SOвӮғ(g)  О”H = вҲ’196 kJ molвҒ»В№ is carried out at 450В°C and ~1 atm. (a) Explain the choice of temperature using both rate and equilibrium arguments. (b) Explain why the pressure used (~1 atm) is much lower than in the Haber process, even though increasing pressure would thermodynamically favour SOвӮғ production. (c) Write the Kc expression for the Contact process equilibrium and state its units. (d) State what would happen to Kc if the temperature were raised to 600В°C.",
        analyze:    "The table below shows the approximate equilibrium yield of NHвӮғ at various temperatures and pressures in the Haber process: [200 atm / 400В°C: 36%], [200 atm / 450В°C: 15%], [200 atm / 500В°C: 9%], [400 atm / 450В°C: 25%], [600 atm / 450В°C: 35%]. Analyse these data to: (a) determine the effect of temperature on yield at constant pressure and connect this to О”H; (b) determine the effect of pressure on yield at constant temperature and connect this to gas mole counts; (c) identify the conditions that give highest yield per pass and explain why these are not used commercially.",
        evaluate:   "Evaluate the following claim about the Haber process: 'The iron catalyst used in the Haber process increases the yield of ammonia per pass by shifting the equilibrium to the right. Without the catalyst, the yield at 450В°C and 200 atm would be much lower than 15%.' Identify every error in this claim, explain what the iron catalyst actually does and does not do, and state what the yield would be at 450В°C and 200 atm without a catalyst (compared to with a catalyst).",
